this month didn’t start out very well for me. honestly i had a really teary and sad day today, nothing went according to plans and i just feel a little disappointed and upset, i spent a lot of energy trying to make something happen that just didn’t, which is sad when you don’t have that much energy to spend. BUT i know i can turn any bad day around. i want a slow, mindful, cosy, and hopeful February, i want to get into the habit of taking proper care of myself because sometimes i still forget. i can’t depend on other people to make me happy so i need to get better at making myself happy !! and that starts with self-care, wonderful necessary life altering self-care❤️ so tonight im gonna write down some positive intentions for this month and be a bit extra kind to myself. it’s really hard to think of self care activities for my monthy self-care challenges (which is why they aren’t really monthly, they are sporadic lmao) so if you have any self-care activities you love please share below because the winter months are difficult and i would love some self-care tips from my favorite online friends ❤️❤️❤️ if your new month started out rocky too, you are not alone !! hugs ❤️

hello, who are you ??

adverse childhood experiences, or ACEs, are traumatic events that happen in childhood. the more ACEs one scores, the higher is the risk of many negative outcomes in adulthood, like physical and mental health problems, substance abuse, higher level of stress hormones, damage to your DNA, etc etc. adverse childhood experiences are preventable, which is why it’s SO important to educate ourselves about the signs of child abuse, and stopping generational trauma by addressing and healing from the things that happened to us as children, so we don’t repeat those traumatic actions made against us. children are a vulnerable group, and it’s our communal responsibility to protect them from harm, because the things that happen to us in childhood can stay with us the rest of our life and affect our adulthood. and on the flip side, we have positive childhood experiences, that helps you feel secure as an adult. it all really starts in childhood, so be kind to your children and each other 💌

i either have a self-care day or a self-scare day, there is absolutely no in between. today was the latter for me 😭😭 which one did u have

i will sit and ruminate about the littlest things, a seed of worry that grows into a huge disaster or fear, to the point that i forget how it even started. but then i’ll quit my job on the spot because of a whim lmao. absolutely no middle ground 😭 i can’t let myself ruminate big stuff because then nothing would ever get decided, and i think that’s for the best honesty. some of the best things that have happened to me were because i just shrugged and said “i guess i can try”. but i’d be nice to not worry so much about the little things. fellow GAD peeps understand me❤️

it’s #eatingdisorderawarenessweek and i’m working on a more in depth infographic but it had this in the draft which i think would make a nice post this week !! the last point is really what got me out of crippling self-hatred. realizing entire industries are profiting by making us feel awful in our own perfectly fine normal bodies made me just want to be happy with myself out of spite lol 😭 all the things i love the most about myself are all to do with my character and the traits that i have nurtured and grown for year and years. the way we look changes so so much and it’s okay and it doesn’t define us and we are so much more than skin and flesh and weight and looks. all the superficial stuff fades and isn’t what we will look back to and treasure once we are older. so wear that cute top, eat that birthday cake, treat yourself like you treat your friends, and start telling yourself that you are worthy of joy no matter what you look like, because the way you look is the least interesting thing about you !!! life is too short to wait to do the things you want to do because you don’t feel like your body isn’t the ideal body. don’t wait to live to your fullest, you are already enough❤️❤️ #edaw

it’s the last day of eating disorder awareness week ! i learnt a lot while researching for this. people talk a lot about anorexia and bulimia but there are so many forms of disordered eating, more than the ones mentioned here even ! eating disorders are really misunderstood and i see a lot of blame being put on people with eating disorders, eating disorders aren’t pretty and i think there’s a lot of stigma and judgement still. eating disorders can be life threatening and they are so so serious so if you recognize these signs and symptoms in yourself or someone you love please reach out and tell someone because it’s not worth it to suffer in silence when recovery is possible and so so worth it !! #eatingdisorderawareness #edaw

on girlhood, and the epidemic that is men’s violence against women and girls for #internationalwomensday 

today i think about all my girls, women, and femme presenting/identifying people. i think about the people fighting for women’s rights all over the world. for my fellow feminists standing up for us even though it’s tiring and hard to believe how this is still a fight. any men reading this, please step up against misogyny, please help protect girls from men’s violence. please educate your friends. protect trans women, protect vulnerable women, protect Black women, protect women of color, protect disabled women, protect the marginalized women who are too often forgotten or talked over in mainstream feminism. protect ALL women. protect women’s rights to our own bodies. not because we are someone’s mother or sister or daughter but because we are human beings. so many parts about being a woman is terrifying and painful and terribly unfair but my favorite part about womanhood is my relationships with other women, i love femininity, i find such safety and warmth with you that feels eternal and sacred and pure, like we are all made from the same stuff and forged by the same pain and driven by the same roaring hope. 

#iwd2023

my brain is loud as per usual 📣 how’s yours right now ?

i’m not a teen anymore going to school with my friends everyday, i work from home and i have days where i don’t have the mental capacity or energy to see others. but i’m also rather extroverted so i have been feeling increasingly lonely after leaving high school and my day jobs. sometimes i really spiral and start to think and worry about if whether my social life will get lesser and lesser the more i age and it can honestly end in tears. 

but I’ve been thinking lots about how i keep allowing myself to place my happiness on other people and that’s not how I want to feel anymore. i want to be happy in my own company !!! 

lately i’ve been learning how to crochet and i’ve been writing fiction again for the first time in YEARS and i’ve started to look forward to spending a weekend day or evening alone just rewatching shows and following crochet tutorials or trying to write a novel !!! and i’m very proud of myself and I feel a lot happier now when someone cancels on me hahaha… being alone doesn’t have to feel lonely if you can have fun with yourself !!! what a realization 😭❤️

it’s world bipolar day today !! 

i have come a long way managing my symptoms and i have gotten to know my tells and signs quite well. when i was younger and my life felt like utter chaos, I was swinging wildly with my moods. i had severe insomnia in my teens and i think that’s what triggered my hypomania so early. my sleep hygiene has improved a lot and now that i work from home and feel more settled in life, i have been able to eliminate a lot of stress as well which has REALLY helped. sleep is EVERYTHING for my bipolar management, i added these two journal entries, the first one shows how i start to feel when my sleep isn’t sufficient, and i feel like hypomania is starting. i think accepting that my bipolar will always be here has helped me check in with myself more often and when I see warning signs, i think of ways to slow down and take care of myself in ways that will help. i try my best to keep a hopeful and positive self-talk about my mental health, while still being honest about how bad reality can be, maybe that’s reflected in my little journal scribbles. it helps me so much, it really teaches your brain to run in a more optimistic and self soothing way, which makes it feel not as hard and permanent. the way i write and articulate my mental health issues has a HUGE impact on how it manifests in my life. outlook is so important !! 

so for my bipolar babes, please reminder to check in with yourself often, and get to know the bipolar side of you well, and please keep track of your triggers !!! once i figured out mine, i have been feeling a lot more stable ❤️ bipolar disorder can be so scary and alienating but there are so many people who know what you are going through, and so many ways to manage your unique journey !! life can get better at the most unexpected times ❤️ #bipolardisorder #worldbipolarday

it’s publication day of my book🥹

as i sit in absolute awe of how far i have come on my journey, my mind goes back in time and i reminisce about young me. i write about her in the book, addressing her in what was our darkest days. “look how far you can go when you cheer yourself on, when you believe in yourself. when you treat yourself with the respect and love you always deserved.” the journey of healing and feeling better is far from over, it is continuing your entire life. but now you have tools, you have done so much work, and it’s okay now to sit in imperfection and just BE !! just breathe and move and laugh and cry. there will be hard days, but you found that light and it will always be with you. that light is hope, the little voice inside urging me to stay, to explore and be curious, to feel without judgement, to exist without shame. 

better, not perfect, because nothing will ever be perfect, and that is okay ! thank you all, because i couldn’t have done this without you. in the least parasocial way, human to human, i love you all and my gratitude is boundless. thank you thank you thank you my little wishfulfillers. and thank you again to @eburybooks for giving me this opportunity !!! a day to celebrate, and many more of those to come. 

all my love,
Matilda

as i’ve spoken about plenty of times here before, when I was a teenager i had social anxiety. my biggest fear was being judged and perceived by other people, i would rather fail a class than have an oral presentation, when i hurt my knee i didn’t want people asking me about my crutches or looking at me so I stayed home a MONTH because i just refused to go. life felt so tiny and every time i avoided something scary, the smaller my world became. less and less people, places, and situations felt safe, i was always feeling sick because of the toll the stress had on my body, it was a really horrible time. the more you feed your fear, the bigger the fear grows, until it has taken complete control and stripped you of your self-esteem, safety, and trust in yourself. 

with the help of cognitive behavioral therapy I started easing into challenging my fears, very small steps that helped me realize that i was braver than i thought, because bravery is a skill you practice. the more times i let things just now awkward or unsure or scary, the more i realized that i can survive those things, and they aren’t so scary after all. and even now i find ways to challenge my fears on the regular. 

one thing i’m really scared of is public speaking, which is something i want to get better at, so i have said yes to so many super scary things that are coming up this month and the next. there’s a part of me that’s saying “what the hell have you done, CANCEL !! you’re gonna make a fool out of yourself !!!” but the bigger and kinder part of myself is answering, “if you show up as yourself, with all the awkward and stuttering parts, you are being yourself and that is who they want to talk to. you don’t have to be amazing or comfortable with something you haven’t done much, it’s okay to be scared. don’t let the fear stop you from growing your confidence.” and it really helps me calm down. 

i am so happy i started exiting my comfort zone, because now i feel like i actually have opportunities and i can be myself without worrying if i will measure up to what other people think i should be like, because all i can be is myself !! 
so face your fears with me this month, we can do it !! ❤️

i have seen so much discourse lately about impulsive and intrusive thoughts, so i made this little cheat sheet. even through intrusive thoughts can be totally normal and harmless, (i think most people can relate to things like standing over a ledge and thinking “hey i could totally just jump to my death right now”, and wondering why your brain confused up such an image. it can be the brain trying to remind you of danger in its own silly way.) but when these thoughts are persistent, it can also be totally life-interfering and scary and shameful so please remember to be respectful with how you talk about things that affect other people deeply 🫶 people with mental illness are always trying to be understood and supported, so when terms get watered down and misused it makes it harder for us to be taken seriously !! and if your impulsiveness or your intrusive thoughts are interfering with your life, please reach out for support or care if you have access !!

i try to think about my mental health conditions with optimism, but sometimes it can be quite nice to just voice everything that makes things hard and sad. i find catharsis in complaining sometimes haha. one of my biggest struggles with mental illness (especially with it being my job too) is identity, figuring out where my mental illness ends and I begin, and wondering who i’d been if i hadn’t been ill. sometimes it feels like mental illness has touched every part of me, even though i logically know that there is so much more to my personality and identity. i can’t allow myself to sit and ruminate too long about everything that feels shitty, but it’s also really important that people hear about the things that make mental illness hard to deal with, because it needs to be taken seriously !! 

so feel free to vent below, what do you find the hardest about living with mental illness ?

politics is a super touchy subject but mental health IS political because the systems we are a part of directly impact our mental health, especially those most vulnerable in our society. for mental health awareness month i would like to see more political action to better support people struggling. my dream is to see a world of community and not commodity, where everyone has access to healthcare and help with no societal or financial hurdles and no policymakers working AGAINST better and more accessible healthcare to pinch pennies and keep poor people poor. some of my mental health issues are chemical for sure, but the older i get the more i realize a lot of my issues are situational and stemming from the stress of my life. i really don’t think we are meant to live the way a lot of us do and it’s hard to find meaning or purpose when all you have time for is work and chores, and you are worried and scared about what will happen next. everyone deserves good quality of life and i really think if we all had that, we wouldn’t be as sick as we are now. but it’s more profitable to sell up-charged drugs for someone’s depression than to change the systems that breeds their depression in the first place. money as the ultimate incentive won’t further humankind but will rob us of empathy and compassion and community. i want change !!!!!!

i have been thinking so much about my younger self lately. when i wrote my book i had to revisit my life and childhood and while it was a great catharsis, it also hurt - it opened up wounds i had tried to glue together. it made me ache for the little girl who always lived on the outside looking in, yearning to relate and connect but didn’t know how. the first chapter is all about how i felt like i was wrong, because i was different. i never fit in anywhere, i was always the “weird one” even in my friend groups. 

that feeling of not belonging stuck with me for so so long, and i realized this week that i don’t feel that way anymore. with my advocacy work, i have found my peers, my community. for the first time in my life, my neurodivergency is a benefit, something that helps me. i don’t feel disabled anymore, because i am allowed to be myself now, the things that make me different is what helps me do my work. i only felt disabled because everyone needed me to think and feel in a way that doesn’t come naturally to me. i feel so at home with other people who have gone through similar things to me, i don’t feel so odd anymore. i don’t need to make or fake politeness, and being open with my mental health and neurodivergence makes me feel safe because people know what to expect now when they meet me. 

so if you feel they way i felt for the majority of my life, just know that there are places for you. and there are so many people working everyday to make EVERYWHERE a space for EVERYONE. so please don’t give up, listen to your body and soul and keep looking for your community, i promise it exists. i’m getting sappy now haha but i’ve been emotional all week. i feel like i’ve finally come home, and i can relax and live authentically for the first time ever without feeling scared of judgement. i love you all and i hope everyone reading this will find their perfect places where you can all be yourselves, because that is just the best, most freeing way to be. 🫶🫶🫶

made this with lovely Alix ( @counsellingwithalix ) who’s a counselor and ambassador for BEAT, busting some myths about eating disorders 🫶 i have noticed there being an almost condescending attitude towards eating disorders, that it’s just insecure suburban white teenage girls who just have a diet phase, or that it’s all about vanity or that all it takes is just to eat to recover. eating disorders are so complex and the societal and emotional causes and risk factors are vast. i really recommend checking out @counsellingwithalix if you haven’t because she posts so much useful and empathic thoughts and advice about easting disorders on her page🩷 and some words from Alix: 

“When a mental health condition is misunderstood, misconceptions form. Due to misinformation, stigma, and shame, many struggle with their illness entirely alone & shy away from reaching out for support.” 

#mentalhealth #mentalhealthawarenessmonth #eatingdisorderawareness

today is world schizophrenia awareness day so this post is about common signs and symptoms of schizophrenia and the lesser known schizoaffective disorder. these two diagnoses are some of the most stigmatized, misunderstood, and demonized mental health conditions. these diagnoses doesn’t get as much spotlight as say depression and anxiety, perhaps because they are so complex and because most people struggle to empathize with symptoms like delusions and hallucinations. 
nonetheless, it’s not as rare or mystical as you might believe, and even though there is no cure, there are ways and treatments to minimize your symptoms and live full, and meaningful lives. people with schizophrenia are often demonized to be dangerous, but they are WAY more likely to be the victim of violence and abuse than to be a perpetrator of it. it can be really scary to experience schizophrenia and schizoaffective disorder so please, please be kind and compassionate to people going through this. if you have schizophrenia or schizoaffective disorder and want to share how if affects you and your life, feel free to share your experiences, or tips and tricks in the comments !! it’s so important to give space to lesser talked about mental health conditions, so we can strengthen our collective understanding and awareness 🫶 #schizophrenia #schizoaffective

i find it hard to give a proper 50/50 in my relationships, and even through I know that no relationship can be a perfect give and take, it still makes me feel a bit guilty sometimes. my energy runs out so fast and i am not the best at the maintaining of relationships, like checking in and reaching out first, so i worry people will see my lack of energy as a lack of interest, you know ??? also i’m terrible to argue with because as soon as things get a bit heated i start crying and freaking out which isn’t productive and disrupts any form of resolution or communication. i’m working on that through, trying to remind myself to not get so wound up and be okay with people being annoyed or mad at me sometimes without feeling so threatened and scared. somehow i was raised in a secure-attachment home and still wound up with an anxious attachment style, funny how that can go. what do you find the hardest when it comes to relationships and mental illness ? doesn’t have to be romantic but can also be platonic or familial !!!

i recently came across the term “pain shopping”. it’s when you look for reasons to be upset, it’s confirming your own pain over and over again, even though you know that nothing good will come of it. it’s like breaking a vase, and instead of cleaning it up and moving along, you leave it there and each time you walk past you stop and look and remember how stupid you are for breaking it, leaving you to wallow in really painful feelings and self-disappointment. 

if you stalk your ex or your exes new partner, if you keep following that influencer who makes you feel like a trashfire every time you see them, if you keep reading those love letters or looking at those old pictures that always just makes you cry, you are pain-shopping. 

i used to pain shop a lot, along with like a million other self-sabotaging actions, and i find the best thing to do is to identify the triggers that make you want to pain shop, and then redirect your attention to some fun or self-soothing activity, and then afterwards treat yourself to literally anything. like training a dog to do a trick hahaha i swear to god it works and then you can remind yourself of how much better you feel when you focus on yourself, and not past things that made you feel bad !!! 💌 do you pain shop, or did you use to ?

this is my favorite xmas post, a needed reminder for those times where you don’t feel in the festive mood. today we celebrate christmas in sweden and i’ve definitely had some christmases where i just wanted to go to bed and sleep forever and more. mental illness doesn’t take breaks because we have something to celebrate, so please be easy on yourself on days where you feel pressured to be happy. 

this is in collaboration with @optionb !! i love this organization, i personally love their HUGE resource library that was especially helpful for me when navigating grief. check them out for tips on how to cope when the holidays are bringing up difficult feelings. head to their holiday resource page at OptionB.Org/Holidays or at the link in their bio. 🩷 and remember that it’s okay to feel however you are feeling today and tomorrow xxx

this year was the best and worst for me all at once. but this december i’ve worked so hard to set up a better, healthier, and more emotionally stable 2024. i hope you guys have a nice new years, be safe and take care 🩷🩷

my ins and outs for this new year !!! my biggest theme for my ins is making healthy choices, instead of self-destructive choices. no forcing myself to go to the gym because i just don’t like it, i’ll go swimming or walking instead. no more excessive drinking, no more buying ten dollar vapes (which is just literally flavored cancer air😭) everyday, no more doing things because “that’s just what people do”.
